# Global coding standards

Objective: code must be **production-grade, enterprise-grade, and easy to maintain for years**.

## Language & structure
- **TypeScript for all new JS code** (no plain `.js`). Typed Python (hints + Pydantic).
- Follow **clean code** principles; small, single-purpose units.
- A file must **not exceed 1000 lines** — split before it does.
- **Prefer `async/await`** over callbacks/`.then` chains.
- Write **comprehensive error handling** (no empty catches; fail loud or handle deliberately).

## Naming
- Meaningful, intention-revealing names for variables and functions.
- **Max 60 characters** for any variable or function name.

## Comments & docs
- Every function has **JSDoc** (TS) / **docstring** (Python): purpose, params, returns, throws.
  Write them so an AI agent can understand intent without reading the body.
- Comments explain **why / intent**, not a line-by-line narration of what the code does.

## Formatting (target; enforced by Prettier/ESLint once wired)
- **2-space** indentation; **no trailing whitespace**; **semicolons required**.
- **Single quotes** for strings in JS/TS; **max line length 100**.

## External references
- Follow the **Google TypeScript Style Guide**; format with **Prettier**; obey the project
  **ESLint** config; see the root `README.md` for setup.

> Existing Phase 0 files are normalized to these formatting rules when ESLint/Prettier is wired.
